hands_on_practices.problem:
Consider a spin-1 particle. In the standard basis of eigenvectors of the $S_z$ operator, which are denoted as $|1\rangle$, $|0\rangle$, and $|-1\rangle$, the spin operator in the x-direction, $S_x$, is represented by the following matrix:

$$
S_x = \frac{\hbar}{\sqrt{2}}
\begin{pmatrix}
0 & 1 & 0 \\
1 & 0 & 1 \\
0 & 1 & 0
\end{pmatrix}
$$

Now, consider the observable defined by the operator $A = S_x^2$. The spectrum of eigenvalues for this operator contains one value that is degenerate, meaning it corresponds to more than one linearly independent eigenvector. Determine the value of this degenerate eigenvalue. Your final answer should be an expression in terms of the reduced Planck constant $\hbar$.
